investment in athletic facilities on-campus. The Wayne Densch Athletic Sports Complex is a major new
mixed-use project planned for the northern end of the University of Central Florida (UCF) Orlando Main
Campus. This project is part of UCF’s plan to remain competitive at the highest level of the National
Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) Division I. UCF’s Athletics Department has identified the
provision of top-notch facilities to the student athletes as one of the key factors in recruiting and
retaining top athletic talent. The inclusion of these facilities on UCF’s Campus is also important to non-

The purpose of the study is to first of all to evaluate the impacts of the proposed Wayne Densch
Athletic Sports Complex on the UCF and surrounding roadway network, including an evaluation of
parking demands. This analysis will be undertaken for two scenarios, i.e., the Base, approved, 2000
Campus Master Plan (CMP) and the revised plan including the football stadium.
The second part of the study will determine the parking demands that will be created by attendees and
users of the Complex, for both of the scenarios noted above. This part of the study will also examine
the existing and projected supply of parking facilities in the area that will be available to meet the
needs of both existing facilities and the planned Athletic Complex. Similar to the traffic impact
analysis, the parking analysis will also examine both scenarios described above.

The analysis of the transportation related impacts of the proposed Athletic Center was separated into
two sections. The first section concerns the evaluation of the more “standard” land uses such as the
office space, convocation center, residential units (student housing), support retail space and the
smaller athletic venues. Since these uses will generally operate on weekdays during standard hours,
they were analyzed using “standard” traffic impact analysis practices and peak periods. Specifically,
traffic analyses for these uses examined weekday impacts during morning and evening peak periods,
generally recognized as 7-9 a.m. for morning peak and 4-6 p.m. for the evening peak period.
The second section focused solely on the projected impacts from the stadium. As currently planned,
the football stadium would hold six to seven football games per year, predominantly on Saturdays
during the fall semester. Most games are expected to start in the afternoon or early evening, generally
In general, the stadium analysis will closely conform to the methodologies outlined in two key
publications, “Managing Travel for Planned Special Events”, by Federal Highway Administration
(FHWA), published in 2003; and, “Transportation Planning and Management for Special Events”,
Synthesis 309 by the National Cooperative Highway Research Program (NCHRP). The synthesis,
published in 2003 surveyed several large venues around the United States and has several case studies.
The FHWA Handbook has a detailed structure that outlines the approach to preparing a feasibility study
When analyzing the football stadium it is important to recognize that this is a “special generator” that
will not be impacting the surrounding roadway system during peak periods generally analyzed under
standard practices. As such, the standard methodologies are not appropriate, as they will not address
the actual impacts of the stadium. If the standard, weekday peak periods (7-9 a.m., and 4-6 p.m.)
were analyzed, the stadium would show essentially no impacts as it would not be in use. As such, a
different analysis period needed to be selected that would more appropriately evaluate the overall
impacts of the stadium. Yearly, semester and weekly analysis periods were considered for the
evaluation of the stadium traffic impacts. After reviewing other related studies, the available traffic
data and the projected operating characteristics of the stadium, a weekly analysis period was selected.

The primary scenario to be analyzed for future parking demand is a sold-out UCF home Football game
with 45,000 attendees. Utilizing the mode split, and average auto occupancy percentages developed in
the trip generation estimates for the stadium, an estimate of the number of vehicles by type was
calculated at just over 11,400 parking spaces are estimated to be required for a sold-out football
game. When this demand of 11,400 spaces is compared to the projected 14,681 parking spaces
calculated in the previous section, it appears that there is an overall surplus of approximately 3,200
spaces. The majority of these spaces will be within a 10-minute walk of the football stadium.

It is therefore recommended that a Transportation Management Program (TMP) be developed that
includes several Traffic Demand Management (TDM) strategies for football game conditions. These
include but are not limited to:
Create a Local Traffic Stakeholder Group – As the planned stadium could have dramatic
impacts on the LOS of surrounding roadways, it is suggested that the University develop a
stakeholder group to plan for and mitigate traffic impacts. The creation of the group will need
to address stakeholder roles and responsibilities, who will led the group meeting schedules,
etc. The group should include, but is not limited to:
Owners of Surrounding Student Housing properties
Increase the Public Transit/Park-N-Ride Mode Share – The existing LYNX service in the area
is limited to three routes with very long headways. The University should determine the
feasibility of working with LYNX to dramatically increase transit to the on-campus transit
center as much as possible. This could also include the creation of specialized, “Golden Knight”
express bus routes from the downtown Orlando area as well as any other surrounding areas
(such as regional malls) determined to have a high concentration of attendees. This will require
a pre-game marketing effort as well as coordination with facility operators as game attendees
Pre-Trip Traveler Information Techniques – The University should investigate a wide range of
communication opportunities in order to modify driver behavior and mode choice. These
include but are not limited to:
Specialized Event and Venue Transportation Guide (incl. Parking)
One specific item that the University is already exploring is the use of directed parking
management. UCF has retained the services of Gameday Management, Inc., to develop a parking
management system that will also help to distribute football traffic to the surrounding roadway
Traffic Management Techniques – There are a wide variety of traffic management techniques
that should be evaluated for applicability to UCF Football game days. These include:
Modifications to existing signal timing patterns
Installation of additional traffic signals that would only operate on games days/special
Installation of special, adaptive signal systems such as the SCOOT System installed by
Orange County on I-Drive that can handle highly-variable traffic flows
Geometric modifications to existing roadways or intersections such as the addition of,
or expansion to turn lanes, etc.
Improve Bicycle Accommodation - The University already enjoys a fair amount of bicycle
mode share due to the campus amenities, extensive trail network and local weather conditions.
Increasing bicycle amenities in the vicinity of t he stadium as well as improving safe access to
the stadium through the use of dedicated bike trails should be evaluated. Secure bicycle
parking should be located close to the stadium entrance. Staffing should be provided to
Guide Signing Program- A combination of static and dynamic message signs are a crucial part
of controlling traffic flows in the vicinity of the stadium. However, in order to be truly
effective, drivers must be “captured” a sufficient distance from campus in order to allow them
to make route decisions. It is therefore recommended that the University partner with FDOT
and OOCEA to secure respective agency approval to locate temporary changeable message signs
(CMS) on surrounding roadway. It is also suggested that the University examine the potential
for the installation of other permanent CMS signs at strategic points around campus to control
Reversible Travel Lanes – As the existing UCF internal roadway system is limited to a
maximum of four lanes on the major ring road, Gemini Boulevard, additional studies should be
conducted to determine the potential to convert Gemini Boulevard to one-way operation so as
to effectively double the overall roadway capacity. This option will require that special
provisions be made for the UCF Shuttles that will be traversing the campus moving attendees
from distant parking facilities to the stadium area.

(i.e., arterial vs. collector) and the maintaining agency’s adopted Level Of Service (LOS) Standard. In

2002 Quality/Level Of Service Handbook is shown below as Figure 2-1.

stations in the vicinity of the UCF Campus.

stakeholder group to plan for and mitigate traffic impacts. The creation of the group will need
to address stakeholder roles and responsibilities, who will led the group meeting schedules,
etc. The group should include, but is not limited to:
Owners of Surrounding Student Housing properties
Increase the Public Transit/Park-N-Ride Mode Share – The existing LYNX service in the area
is limited to three routes with very long headways. The University should determine the
feasibility of working with LYNX to dramatically increase transit to the on-campus transit
center as much as possible. This could also include the creation of specialized, “Golden Knight”
express bus routes from the downtown Orlando area as well as any other surrounding areas
(such as regional malls) determined to have a high concentration of attendees. This will require
a pre-game marketing effort as well as coordination with facility operators as on-site parking
will be consumed by game attendees.
Trip Traveler Information Techniques – The University should investigate a wide range of
communication opportunities in order to modify driver behavior and mode choice. These
include but are not limited to:
Specialized Event and Venue Transportation Guide (incl. Parking)
One specific item that the University is already exploring is the use of directed parking
management. UCF has retained the services of Gameday management, Inc., to develop a
parking management system that will also help to distribute football traffic to the surrounding
Traffic Management Techniques – There are a wide variety of traffic management techniques
that should be evaluated for applicability to UCF Football game days. These include:
Modifications to existing signal timing patterns
Installation of additional traffic signals that would only operate on games days/special
Installation of special, adaptive signal systems such as the SCOOT System installed by
Orange County on I-Drive that can handle highly-variable traffic flows
Geometric modifications to existing roadways or intersections such as the addition of, or
The University already enjoys a fair amount of bicycle
mode share due to the campus amenities, extensive trail network and local weather conditions.
Increasing bicycle amenities in the vicinity of t he stadium as well as improving safe access to
the stadium through the use of dedicated bike trails should be evaluated. Secure bicycle
parking should be located close to the stadium entrance. Staffing should be provided to
Guide Signing Program- A combination of static and dynamic message signs are a crucial part
of controlling traffic flows in the vicinity of the stadium. However, in order to be truly
effective, drivers must be “captured” a sufficient distance from campus in order to allow them
to make route decisions. It is therefore recommended that the University partner with FDOT
and OOCEA to secure respective agency approval to locate temporary changeable message signs
(CMS) on surrounding roadway. It is also suggested that the University examine the potential
for the installation of other permanent CMS signs at strategic points around campus to control
Reversible Travel Lanes – As the existing UCF internal roadway system is limited to a
maximum of four lanes on the major ring road, Gemini Boulevard, additional studies should be
conducted to determine the potential to convert Gemini Boulevard to one-way operation so as
to effectively double the overall roadway capacity. This option will require that special
provisions be made for the UCF Shuttles that will be traversing the campus moving attendees
from distant parking facilities to the stadium area.
As one of the highest traffic peaks will occur after the game is over,
one innovative approach to spread out the departure traffic demand would be to hold some
event that would keep some of the attendees on campus for a period of at least an hour after
As it appears that there will be sufficient overall parking on Campus, the primary challenge will be to
devise a shuttle system that will safely and efficiently move attendees in a relatively short time. UCF
will need to investigate the option of temporarily expanding their shuttle fleet for game days to handle
the increased demands – both on and off campus.

The University of Central Florida’s Department of Athletics is committed to competitive
excellence at the highest level of NCAA Division I. It is important to identify the important
factors in successful recruitment and retention of quality student-athletes and this is a vital
component in the success of any athletic program. Making top-notch facilities available to our
coaches and student-athletes is critical in the success of UCF Athletics. It is no secret that young
men and women across the nation identify with colleges and universities in a large part for their
success in athletics. If the young man or woman is not a student-athlete, chances are they will
want to attend athletic events for entertainment or social reasons to complete the campus
experience. Developing the current master plan of facilities is important in terms of athletic
excellence and the experience we provide the student body.
Over the past couple of years, UCF Athletics has conducted a number of facilities development
projects including enhancements to the Track & Soccer Field, completion of the Baseball
Stadium (Jay Bergman Field), completion of 5 practice fields (2 soccer, 2 football, 1 baseball)
and the first phase of the Softball Stadium which included the backstop, scoreboard, flag pole,
field, dugouts, bullpens and the batting cage. In addition, UCF Athletics is taking one of the
biggest steps in program history by building the new Wayne Densch Sports Center to facilitate
the entire football operation along with Strength and Conditioning/Sports Medicine to be utilized
by all UCF student athletes. All of this progress is only the beginning of a race to raise the level
There are several components to this master plan which will provide every sport and support unit
in UCF Athletics with a new or renovated home. The new Convocation Center (with structured
parking) will provide a home for Men’s and Women’s Basketball, the renovation of the existing
UCF Arena will enhance the facilities available for Volleyball. The completion of the UCF
Softball Stadium will give our softball program everything it needs to be successful.
Development of a Phase II at the Baseball Stadium will add more seats to Jay Bergman Field and
give our baseball program the opportunity to host post season play, which gives the program a
better chance of success. Building an Aquatics Center will help UCF Athletics to enhance
opportunities for female student-athletes as we add swimming, diving, and possibly water polo
and synchronized swimming as women’s sports. Additional Practice Fields will give UCF
Athletics the ability to further enhance opportunities for female student-athletes by possibly
adding lacrosse and/or field hockey as other future sports. A new Tennis Center will help our
Men’s and Women’s Tennis programs to be able to host conference championship tournaments,
as well as provide a home for the program they can call their own. The planned Fieldhouse will
give UCF sports teams needed protection from lightning and inclement weather. An Athletics
Administration Building will allow UCF Athletics to have a central location for the
administration of the athletics department and will include the academic support element,
student-athlete welfare center, and student cafeteria. There also needs to be a stadium and new
homes for Track & Field, Cross Country, and Men’s and Women’s Soccer in the vicinity of the
existing Track & Soccer Field, i.e. an athletic village capable of completely sustaining student-
athletes, with possible student housing and classrooms.
The mission of UCF Athletics is: “…to provide our student-athletes the opportunity to
participate in a quality intercollegiate athletics experience that allows them to grow athletically
and academically, and serves as an integral component of their total educational experience at
UCF Athletics enhances the visibility of the University by serving as a portal to broaden and
strengthen interest in and involvement with the University on a local, regional, and national
level. UCF Athletics also provides a rallying point to unite the diverse elements the University
serves – the student body, the campus community, the alumni, the metropolitan community and
In order to help us fulfill the mission, the Department of Athletics will embrace the following
• To develop and maintain a highly competitive and sound athletics program – reaching a
standard of excellence in athletics consistent with the mission of the University.
